| | `var` | `let` | `const` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Scope | Function | Block | Block |
| Hoisted? | Yes (initialized as `undefined`) | Yes (but TDZ — can't use before declaration) | Yes (but TDZ) |
| Reassignable? | Yes | Yes | No |
| Redeclarable? | Yes | No | No |

**Use `const` by default.** Switch to `let` when you need to reassign. Never use `var`.

The key gotcha with `var`:
```javascript
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);
}
// Prints: 3, 3, 3 (var is function-scoped, shared across iterations)

for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100);
}
// Prints: 0, 1, 2 (let is block-scoped, each iteration gets its own i)
```

Note: `const` prevents reassignment, not mutation. You can still modify the contents of a `const` object or array:
```javascript
const arr = [1, 2, 3];
arr.push(4);      // fine
arr = [5, 6, 7];  // TypeError
```

```javascript
const highValueItems = arr.filter((item) => item.score > 5);

const result = {};
for (const item of highValueItems) {
  result[item.score] = item.value * 2;
}
```

I made assumptions about what `a` and `b` mean — rename to whatever they actually represent.

Changes:
- **Named variables** instead of single letters
- **Simple loop** instead of chained `.map().reduce()` — the reduce-to-object pattern is clever but hard to read at a glance
- **Same behavior**, easier to debug (you can set breakpoints, log intermediate values)

The one-liner chains `filter → map → reduce` which forces readers to mentally track three transformations and an accumulator shape. A loop is more code but takes half the time to understand.
